    "With the point at infinity on the boundary removed, we can choose to describe the theory by a flat metric and the coordinates Φ, γ and γ are well-defined.",
    "This can be made quite explicit for the classical j = 1 2 solution of section 4.4 with the divergence of ϕ at the removed point becoming particularly apparent.We can translate the global coordinates of (4.15) to Wakimoto-adapted coordinates [21] by first defining r = sinh ρ ≥ 0 andϕ = t + 1 2 log(1 + r 2), γ = r √ 1 + r 2 e -t+iθ, γ = r √ 1 + r 2 e -t-iθ.",
